text.tspan: Actor-based Toolkit for Interactive Language Education in Python
created specially for the Advanced Python Summer School
from John DeNero and Dan Klein (UC berkeley)

flowRoot.flowPara: The project is done collaboratively: 30 students are divided in 5 groups (6 students per group). Each team has access to a git repository, hosted on a private server. The code used for the contest has to be in the main branch of git repository. If the code fails to import or raises an error, a random move is done.
Eating: when a Bot eats a food pellet, the food is permanently removed and one point is scored for that bot's team.
Timeout: Each player only has 3 second to return a valid move. If it doesn't, a random move is executed. (All later returned values are discarded.).
Eating another Bot: When a Bot is eaten by an opposite Destroyer, it returns to its starting point (as a harvester). 5 points are attributed for eating an opponent.
Winning: A game ends when either one team has eaten all of it's opponent food pellets, or the team with more points after 300 rounds.
Observations: Bots can only observe an opponent exact location if they or their teammate are within 5 squares of their opponent bot. If they are further away, the opponent's position are noised
The board consists of a maze, separated in two zones: a homezone and the ennemy's homezone. The maze is generated automatically at the beginning of each game. There is no backend.
Each Bot is controlled by a Player
Game ends when all food pellets are eaten
